The term "'''abominable fancy'''" was first used by [[Frederic Farrar]] for the long-standing [[Christian]] idea that the [[eternal punishment]] of the [[damnation|damned]] in [[Hell]] would entertain the saved.<ref>''The Decline of Hell: Seventeenth-Century Discussions of Eternal Torment.'' Walker DP. Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1964</ref> According to [[Philip C. Almond]], this view was held by several early Christian philosophers, including [[Augustine]],  [[Tertullian]],  [[Thomas Aquinas]] and [[Peter Lombard]].<ref>Philip C. Almond, ''Heaven and Hell in Enlightenment England'', p.97. {{ISBN|978-0521101257}}</ref><ref>Alice Bennett, ''Afterlife and Narrative in Contemporary Fiction'', p.204. {{ISBN|1137022698}}.</ref>

