Saint '''Abran''' ([[Breton language|Breton]] for 'Abraham'), also known as '''Gibrian''', was a 6th-century Irish [[hermit]] in Brittany.
He was born in [[Ireland]] and with eight of his siblings traveled to [[Brittany]]. St. Abran and his siblings chose of life of devotion to [[Trinity|God]] in the [[Consecrated life|consecrated religious life]]. He lived in a [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]] on the [[Marne River]], which had been given to him by [[Saint Remigius]].
Abran and his siblings are all considered [[saint]]s for their positive [[Christian]] influence upon the [[Breton people]].
Saint Abran's [[feast day]] is 8 May on the [[Western Rite Orthodox]] and [[Roman Catholic Church]] calendars.
