{{Orphan|date=July 2018}}
'''Alia Al Mansoori''' (born July/23/2002) is an Emirati teenage pupil at [[Al Mawakeb School]]. In 2017 she won the Genes in Space UAE competition, with a proposal to study how exposure to space affects the health of live organisms at cellular level. Her experiment was loaded onto the August 2017 [[SpaceX CRS-12]] mission.<ref>James Langton, [https://www.thenational.ae/uae/science/dreams-of-emirati-teenager-alia-al-mansoori-launched-into-space-1.619762 Dreams of Emirati teenager Alia Al Mansoori launched into space], August 14, 2017.</ref>
Al Mansoori's experiment studied the expression of [[heat-shock proteins]] in space, establishing that the genes turning them on could be detected.<ref name="Vice">Kaleigh Rogers, [https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/kznnjx/the-teenager-who-sent-an-experiment-to-space-and-dreams-of-visiting-mars The Teenager Who Sent An Experiment to Space and Dreams of Visiting Mars], ''motherboard.vice.com'', January 9, 2018.</ref>
Al Mansoori plans to study genetics at university,<ref name="Vice"/> ultimately pursuing postgraduate study to become an [[astronaut]]. Her dream "is to be the first Emirati woman to visit Mars".<ref>Wam, [https://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/my-dream-is-to-be-the-first-emirati-woman-to-go-to-mars-alia-al-mansoori-2017-10-12-1.660227 "My dream is to be the first Emirati woman to go to Mars": Alia Al Mansoori], ''[[Emirates 24/7]]'', October 12, 2007.</ref>
