{{Infobox royalty | name = Catherine Michelle | image =Catalinamicaelaspain65.jpg | caption= '' A Lady in a Fur Wrap'' - Caterina Micaela of Austria |image_size= | consort = yes | succession = [[Duchess consort of Savoy]] | reign = 18 March 1585 – 6 November 1597 | birth_date = 10 October 1567 | birth_place = [[Madrid]], Spain | death_date = {{death date and age|1597|11|6|1567|10|10|df=y}} | death_place = [[Turin]], Italy | burial_place = | spouse = {{marriage|[[Charles Emmanuel I, Duke of Savoy]]|1584}} | issue = {{plainlist| *[[Victor Amadeus I, Duke of Savoy|Victor Amadeus I]] *[[Emanuel Filibert of Savoy|Emanuel Filibert, Viceroy of Sicily]] *[[Margaret of Savoy, Vicereine of Portugal|Margaret, Duchess of Mantua]] *[[Princess Isabella of Savoy|Isabella, Hereditary Princess of Modena]] *[[Maurice of Savoy|Prince-Cardinal Maurice]] *[[Thomas Francis, Prince of Carignano]] }} | issue-link = #Family | house = [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]] | father = [[Philip II of Spain]] | mother = [[Elisabeth of Valois]] | religion = [[Roman Catholicism]] }}
'''Catherine Michelle of Spain''' ({{Lang-es|Catalina Micaela de Austria}}; 10 October 1567 – 6 November 1597) was a Duchess consort of Savoy who served as Regent of Savoy several times during the absence of her spouse, [[Charles Emmanuel I, Duke of Savoy]]. As the youngest surviving daughter of [[Philip II of Spain]] and [[Elisabeth of Valois]], she was the sister of [[Infanta Isabella Clara Eugenia of Spain|Isabella Clara Eugenia]], [[Governor of the Habsburg Netherlands]].<ref>Vincent Joseph Pitts, ''Henri IV of France: His Reign and Age'', (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2009), 311.</ref>
==Biography== [[File:Catalina Micaela of Spain by Alonso Sánchez Coello.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of Infanta Catalina Micaela of Austria by [[Alonzo Sanchez Coello]]]] Catherine Michelle was described as beautiful, intelligent, arrogant and well aware of her high social status. She had a good relationship with her father and exchanged letters with him after her marriage. Charles Emmanuel I suggested the marriage as a way of gaining Spanish support for his plans to expand Savoy on the coast of the then weakened France. The wedding took place in Zaragoza on 11 March 1585 and the couple made their entrance to Turin in Savoy 10 August 1585.
Catherine Michelle was initially unpopular because of her arrogance and attempts to introduce Spanish pomp, ceremony and way of dress to the Court in Turin. However, she soon gained respect because of her political and diplomatic skill, which she used to defend the autonomy of Savoy against Spain.<ref>Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani - Volume 22 (1979)</ref> She refused the Spanish offer to install a Spanish garrison in Turin from Milan with the excuse of giving her a life guard.<ref>Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani - Volume 22 (1979)</ref> She is reported to have had great influence on Charles Emmanuel I and to have reformed him for the better. She also served as regent several times during the absence of the duke on military campaigns, such as during the Lyon campaign in 1594.<ref>Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani - Volume 22 (1979)</ref> Catherine Michelle also benefited cultural life in Savoy, founded many new buildings including an art gallery and invited several artists such as [[Torquato Tasso]], [[Chiabrera]], [[Marini]], [[Tassoni]] and [[Botero]].
Catherine Michelle died near the end of 1597; she had miscarried earlier that year. Her father died the following year. Her sister Isabella married [[Albert VII, Archduke of Austria]], and later became [[Governess of the Netherlands]].
==Family== [[File:Alonso Sánchez Coello (Werkstatt) - Infantin Katharina Michaela von Spanien - 5282 - Bavarian State Painting Collections.jpg|thumb|240px|Infanta Catherine Michelle of Spain]] In 1584, she married [[Charles Emmanuel I, Duke of Savoy]].<ref>[[Yves-Marie Bercé]], ''The Birth of Absolutism: A History of France, 1598-1661'', (MacMillan Press Ltd, 1996), 8.</ref> This marriage produced ten children:
* Philip Emanuel (1586–1605) * [[Victor Amadeus I of Savoy|Victor Amadeus]] (1587–1637)<ref>Paola Rapelli, ''Symbols of Power in Art'', (Getty Publications, 2011), 265</ref> * [[Emanuel Filibert of Savoy]], (1588–1624), Spanish [[Viceroy of Sicily]], (1622–24).<ref>Paola Rapelli, ''Symbols of Power in Art'', 265</ref> * [[Margaret of Savoy, Vicereine of Portugal|Margaret]] (1589–1655), married [[Francesco IV Gonzaga]] of [[Mantua]] * [[Princess Isabella of Savoy|Isabella]] (1591–1626), married [[Alfonso III d'Este]], duke of [[Modena]] * [[Maurice of Savoy|Maurice]], a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] (1593–1657) *Maria Apollonia, a nun in Rome (1594–1656) *Francesca Caterina, a nun in [[Biella]] (1595–1640) *[[Thomas Francis, Prince of Carignano]] (1596–1656), Founder of the House of [[Savoy-Carignano]] and ancestor of the erstwhile ruling Family of Italy *Anna (born 1597)
